description:
Currently `write_batch()` catches ALL database errors as warnings and continues. This hides systemic failures (disk full, database corruption) that will affect every subsequent file.

**Current behavior:**
```rust
Err(e) => {
    warn!(file = %data.relative_path.display(), error = %e, "Failed to write file");
}
```

**Problem:** If disk fills up after 50% of files, user sees 5000 warnings instead of one clear error.

**Suggested improvement:**
```rust
const MAX_CONSECUTIVE_FAILURES: usize = 5;
let mut consecutive_failures = 0;

for data in batch.drain(..) {
    match Self::write_single_file(db, &data) {
        Ok(_) => { consecutive_failures = 0; }
        Err(e) => {
            consecutive_failures += 1;
            if consecutive_failures >= MAX_CONSECUTIVE_FAILURES {
                return Err(e);  // Systemic failure, stop
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Trade-off:** Need to distinguish file-specific errors (bad data) from systemic errors (disk full, corruption).

